\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Textbook quantum mechanics asserts that, given a quantum spin system described
 by the wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}=\frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{2}\fket{\ps\frac{1}{2}}+\frac{\sqrt{4-\pi}}{2}\fket{\minus\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 and given the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}=\frac{\hbar}{2}(\fproj{\ps\frac{1}{2}}-\fproj{\minus\frac{1}{2}})$
\end_inset

, then the probability of observing the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\ps\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 (with post-measurement state 
\begin_inset Formula $\fket{\ps\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 and the probability of observing the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\minus\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 (with post-measurement state 
\begin_inset Formula $\fket{\minus\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 According to the frequency interpretation of probability, the above assertion
 implies that when performing a very large number of experiments on quantum
 systems described by wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

, a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 of the experiments will result in the observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\ps\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 and the remaining fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 will result in the observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\minus\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality, i.e., in an actual experiment, simulation, or computation, bounded
 by space, time, and energy resources, the situation is much fuzzier: (i)
 we cannot 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 prepare the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

; (ii) we cannot build a measurement apparatus corresponding 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 to observable 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}$
\end_inset

; and (iii) we cannot prepare 
\emph on
exact
\emph default
 replicas of any state.
 In other words, we can only perform a limited number of experiments on
 quantum systems closely related to wave function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\psi}$
\end_inset

 and using an apparatus that closely approximates observable 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Given any fixed resources, these experiments will 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 result in the 
\emph on
exact
\emph default
 fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\ps\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 of observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\minus\frac{\hbar}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, these experiments can be viewed as a method (algorithm) to calculate
 the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and it is known that the state of the art algorithms for computing the
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th binary digit of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 require on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n\log^{O\left(1\right)}\left(n\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 operations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "journals/moc/BaileyBP97"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, calculating the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 appears to require more and more physical resources as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gets larger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of this is well-known and holds in both the classical and quantum worlds.
 In the classical world, these observations are believed to be well-understood
 approximations to an idealized independent reality that can continuously
 approached with more and more resources.
 The question in the quantum world is more subtle; it is not evident at
 all that this resource-aware perspective does not alter the very foundations
 of quantum mechanics.
 Indeed taking such resource bounds into consideration is what founded computer
 science as a discipline and has become crucial for understanding the very
 nature of computation.
 Following Feynman
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feynman1982Simulating"

\end_inset

, Landauer
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landauer1996188"

\end_inset

, and others, one might argue that this resource-bounded perspective is
 also crucial for understanding the very nature of physical processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous work, we analyzed the wave function description of quantum systems
 from a resource-bounded perspective.
 Technically, instead of postulating that quantum states are rays in a Hilbert
 space, i.e., we instead used special finite fields whose size reflected the
 available resources.
 \SpecialChar ldots

\end_layout

