\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a 
\emph on
theoretical
\emph default
 investigation of 
\emph on
experimental
\emph default
 physics using 
\emph on
computational
\emph default
 methods.
 All experiments and computations are processes bounded in space, time,
 energy, and other resources
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jaeger2007,Piccinini2015"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, for centuries, the mathematical formalization of such processes has
 been founded on the infinitely precise real or complex numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable,blum2012complexity"

\end_inset

.
 Our purpose here is to exploit the consequences of replacing infinitely-specifi
ed quantum probabilities by finite number of intervals used in interval-valued
 probability measures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(IVPM); in particular, we show that a quantum IVPM may not be induced by
 a infinitely-precise state, but it might be more and more likely to be
 identified to a particular state when the measurement resources increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, almost every description of quantum mechanics, quantum computation,
 or quantum experiments refers to entities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rme$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, etc (see, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Redhead1987-REDINA,544199,Mermin2007"

\end_inset

).
 From a computational perspective, such numbers do not exist in their entirety
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

for free
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kent1999,CliftonKent2000"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For example, the state of the art algorithms for computing the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th binary digit of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 require on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n\log^{O\left(1\right)}\left(n\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 operations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "journals/moc/BaileyBP97"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, simply referring to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 requires more and more resources as 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gets larger.
 Taking such resource bounds into consideration is what founded computer
 science as a discipline and is crucial for understanding the very nature
 of computation and, following Feynman
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feynman1982Simulating"

\end_inset

, Landauer
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Landauer1996188"

\end_inset

, and others, for understanding the very nature of physical processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have been revisiting quantum mechanics, quantum information, and quantum
 computation from this resource-aware perspective.
 Our initial results in that domain showed how subtle the issues can be
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "usat,geometry2013,DQT2014"

\end_inset

: a straightforward replacement of the complex numbers by a finite field
 yields a variant of quantum mechanics in which computationally hard problems
 like UNIQUE-SAT (which decides whether a given Boolean formula is unsatisfiable
 or has exactly one satisfying assignment
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Valiant198685,Papadimitriou1993,AroraBarak2009"

\end_inset

) can be deterministically solved in constant time.
 To eliminate such unrealistic theories requires delicate analysis of the
 structure of the Hilbert space, the process of observation, and the notion
 of probability teasing apart their reliance on the infinitely precise real
 numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "geometry2013,DQT2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, we shift focus from the infinitely-specified but not directly
 observable quantum states, to observable measurable properties of quantum
 systems and their probabilities.
 Furthermore, we insist that our theories of measurement and probability
 only refer to finitely communicable evidence within feasible computational
 bounds.
 It follows that states, observations, and probabilities all become 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, i.e., specified by intervals of confidence that can only increase in precision
 if the available resources increase proportionally.
 Our notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy quantum mechanics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is related to existing work
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GranikCaulfield1996,Pykacz2013,SNL2009,Gudder2005,aerts1993physical"

\end_inset

 but, as will be explained in more detail, is distinguished by its unique
 computational character.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will begin by reviewing existing work that recasts classical probability
 spaces in a resource-aware setting and move to aim at recasting quantum
 probability and quantum measurement.
 In particular, we develop a measurement framework based on quantum IVPM.
 Surprisingly, we found a quantum IVPM which can not be induced by a state,
 while Shapley proved a classical convex IVPM can always be induced by a
 classical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapley1971,Grabisch2016"

\end_inset

, and Gleason proved a infinitely-specified quantum probabilities measure
 can always be induced by a quantum state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, a quantum IVPM could still correspond to many possible states
 if it is broken into pieces.
 Our examples also suggest that a quantum IVPM could be more and more likely
 induced by a state while the intervals become sharper, i.e., the measurement
 resources increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since Gleason's theorem supports the idea of von Neumann to define a state
 as a density matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Varadarajan2008"

\end_inset

, a density matrix might not be a adequate imprecise quantum state.
 Instead, a imprecise quantum state might be more like an interactive system
 suggested by Quantum Bayesianism or QBism
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FuchsSchack2013,FuchsMerminSchack2014,VonBaeyer2016"

\end_inset

, which would interact differently with different clients.
 Furthermore, the validity the fundamental theorems of quantum mechanics
 followed up by Gleason's theorem, such as Bell
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bell1964,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

 and Kochen-Specker
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochenspecker1967,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

, might need to be reassessed based on our imprecise measurement.
 Our research then might provide a new insight to the old debate among Meyer,
 Mermin, and others about whether finite precision measurement would nullify
 the Kochen-Specker theorem or not
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.83.3751,Mermin1999,BarrettKent2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

