\begin_layout Standard
The conventional definition of a probability space builds upon the field
 of real numbers.
 In more detail, a probability space consists of a 
\emph on
sample space
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, a space of 
\emph on
events
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, and a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas$
\end_inset

 mapping events in 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 to the real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We will only consider 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 sets of events and restrict our attention to non-empty finite sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as the sample space.
 The space of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 includes every possible subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

: it is the powerset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}=\set{E}{E\subseteq\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 For future reference, we emphasize that events are the primary notion of
 interest and that the sample space is a convenient artifact that allows
 us to treat events as sets obeying the laws of Boolean algebra
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boole1948,Redhead1987-REDINA,Griffiths2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


