 we would express the probability in this case as the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\frac{1213}{3204},\frac{1224}{3204}\right]$
\end_inset

 expressing that we are certain that the event has probability at least
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1213}{3204}$
\end_inset

 but it is possible that it would have probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1224}{3204}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to re-express the above observations is that the calculus of
 probabilities requires all probabilities to be 
\emph on
coherent
\emph default
 (e.g., the probability of the union of two disjoint events is the sum of
 their probabilities).
 But given limited resources, the calculation of a probability measure can
 only be approximate and hence the probabilities cannot be absolutely guaranteed
 to be coherent in the ideal sense.
\end_layout

