\begin_layout Section
Why Empty Core?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The possibility that a convex quantum interval-valued probability measure
 has an empty core departs from the classical case.
 To understand the meaning of it, we will first study how to recover the
 non-empty core with extra conditions.
 We will then consider having an empty core as an legitimate result, and
 understand its consequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convexity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possibility for having an empty core is that the definition of quantum
 convexity is too weak.
 On one hand, strengthening equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumInterval-valuedProbability-Convex"

\end_inset

) to non-commuting projectors
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 is unlikely to succeed because the product of non-commuting projectors
 is not a projector.
 On the other hand, strengthening equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumInterval-valuedProbability-Convex"

\end_inset

) among commuting projectors cannot guarantee a non-empty core as well if
 we follow what people strengthen convexity classically.
 Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:QuantumInterval-valuedProbability-Convex"

\end_inset

) classically is a special case of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\mu}'\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{N}E_{i}\right)+\sum_{{{\scriptstyle I\subseteq\left\{ 1,\ldots,N\right\} }\atop {\scriptstyle \left|I\right|\textrm{ is odd}}}}\bar{\mu}'\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}E_{i}\right)\subseteq\sum_{{{\scriptstyle I\subseteq\left\{ 1,\ldots,N\right\} }\atop {\scriptstyle \left|I\right|\textrm{ is even}}}}\bar{\mu}'\left(\bigcap_{i\in I}E_{i}\right)\label{eq:Dempster-Shafer-game}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}'$
\end_inset

 is a classical interval-valued probability measure.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}'$
\end_inset

 satisfies equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Dempster-Shafer-game"

\end_inset

) for all set of event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ E_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}\subseteq2^{\Omega}$
\end_inset

, then the left-end point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}'$
\end_inset

